            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Todd Chan\u2019s identity was forged in the space between expectations. Born in Walnut Creek to a young, single white mother, he was given his surname at age seven when his mother married Stephen Chan, a kind and pragmatic accountant who became the only father Todd ever knew. Growing up a white kid with a Chinese last name in the suburbs, Todd always felt slightly out of sync, a feeling that drew him not to rebellion, but to curation. He found his calling in the cluttered racks of East Bay thrift stores, seeing stories and potential where others saw old clothes.\n\nRejecting the four-year university path his stepfather hoped for, Todd moved to San Francisco in his early twenties and enrolled at the Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising. The city was an immediate fit. He earned his Associate's degree and landed a job at \"Epilogue,\" a high-end vintage boutique in Hayes Valley. He never left. Over two decades, he worked his way from stockroom grunt to the trusted store manager, his eye for period-specific stitching and fabric becoming legendary among regulars. A major turning point came in his late thirties after the amicable end of a long-term relationship. The breakup, while painful, solidified his identity as a proudly independent man whose life was his work, his friends, and his neighborhood.\n\nToday, Todd\u2019s life is a finely tailored routine. He resides in a rent-controlled, one-bedroom apartment on Page Street, a sanctuary filled with mid-century furniture, obscure vinyl, and a walk-in closet that\u2019s a museum of textile history. His 1.1-mile walk to the boutique is his daily meditation, a ritual of nodding to fellow shopkeepers and grabbing an oat latte from his favorite cafe. His social life consists of a small, loyal circle of industry friends and bi-weekly dinners with his now-retired parents.\n\nAt 48, Todd is content but not complacent. He\u2019s a fixture in Hayes Valley, a quiet pillar of the community he helped build. His deepest aspiration is to one day buy \"Epilogue\" from its aging owner, ensuring its legacy continues under his care. He doesn\u2019t dream of riches, but of turning the key to a place that is finally, wholly, his own."
